******
[2] Comment on social media and vaccination
Date: Thu 20 Dec 2018
From: TJ John <tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in>

It is indeed disappointing and distressing to read about refusals to give oral polio vaccine [OPV] to children in Pakistan based on social media messages. The trigger event of a 2 month old child dying on day 3 after a dose of OPV cannot have been caused by the vaccine. Maternal antibodies protect infants from vaccine-associated paralytic polio (VAPP) during the 1st 4 months of life. Even in the most unlikely event of the mother not being immune, the child's illness could not have been VAPP, which has a minimum incubation period of 4 days. This information must be shared through social media.

However, when parents ask if OPV is safe, what do we answer? How can risk of VAPP, as small as it is, and of VDPV, as rare as it is, be communicated? That is a dilemma.

The benefit-risk ratio of OPV was excellent as the polio eradication drive began, with 350 000 wild virus polio and about 500 VAPP annually. Polio experts knew that the ratio would become unfavourable as the burden of wild virus polio declined to about 5000 per year, while VAPP would remain at [approximately] 500. At that point, inactivated polio vaccine [IPV] was the vaccine of choice to protect children from VAPP and from wild virus polio. IPV through EPI and OPV by campaigns should have been the ideal method until polio was eradicated, when OPV could have been withdrawn quite safely.

Now our best tactic is to ensure IPV through EPI; no child has developed polio after taking 3 doses. If the 1st dose is given at or after 14 weeks, and the 2nd dose after a gap of 4 or more months, 2 doses will suffice for assured immunity. Polio, in spite of multiple doses of OPV, is the reason why children have to be accessed again and again, seeding suspicion of various motives by the polio programme. As the eradication programme is managed by Global Polio Eradication Initiative and country governments and agencies, all of us have the moral duty to promote IPV in EPI, while GPEI struggles to ensure OPV coverage of as near 100% as possible, with multiple -- more than 5-10 -- doses per child. The cost may seem high, but the cost of failure of eradication is worse.

--
T Jacob John
former (retired) professor of clinical virology
Christian Medical College
Vellore, India
<tjacobjohn@yahoo.co.in>

[As always, ProMED-mail would like to thank Dr Prof T Jacob John for his very insightful comments. This unfortunate infant death referred to in the above comment was diagnosed as due to pneumonia and not related to the vaccine (see Poliomyelitis update (60): Pakistan, negative impact of social media 20181219.6214362). But Prof TJ John is correct when he raises the conundrum of the shift of the risk benefit ratio of administering OPV alone, without 1st protecting the infants/children with IPV. We are very much on the "same page" with respect to concerns re: the shifting of the risk benefit equation for the use of OPV alone. - Mod.MPP]
